Query with Keywords
When creating document query and using keywords to narrow the search it is important to know about searching for NULL or keywords that have not been assigned a value on a document.

The short answer, it is not possible. Why? Since OnBase is a database driven application, keywords and there values are associated with a particular document which is stored in the database. However, if a value has not been assigned to a Keyword associated to a Document then there would be no row in the database to identify that particular Keyword. So, when working with a document query it would not be possible to search for a NULL or keyword without an associated value as it would not exists in the database and therefore not provide anything to search.

Although, finding documents that do not have a keyword associated is still possible. Using the ExecuteQueryResults method allow the ability to include additional parameters to the query returning keywords without an associated value. Please refer to *placeholde

Keywords Overview
Keywords are used in every OnBase solution, and are essential for efficient document management and retrieval. Keywords are an important part of how OnBase because they provide methods to effectively index, classify, differentiate, and retrieve documents.

There are three classifications of OnBase Keywords and depending on your solution may contain all 1 or many classifications.

Standalone

Single Instance Keyword Group (SIKG)

Multi-Instance Keyword Group (MIKG)

Keyword Classification
Standalone Keywords
Standalone Keywords are the most commonly used. These individual keywords are not bound any other keywords and may have multiple instances of the keyword value on a single document.

Single Instance Keyword Group
This is a collection of Keyword Types assigned as a whole to a Document Type. Unlike Standalone Keywords, Keyword Types assigned to the group may not contain more than one instance.

Multi-Instance Keyword Group
This is a collection of Keyword Types assigned as a whole to a Document Type. Unlike SIKGs, this group of Keyword Types may be repeated on a document. Furthermore, a MIKG respects the relationships among the Keyword Types within the Keyword Type Group.

Keyword Datasets
Keyword Types can be configured in OnBase to use Dataset. A Dataset provides the user the ability to choose preset Keyword Values. In the OnBase Clients, this is presented as a select or drop-down textbox.

Datasets
Standalone Keyword Dataset
Standalone Datasets are unique to the Keyword Type configured in OnBase Configuration. They are single purpose select or drop-down values.

Cascading Keyword Dataset
Cascading Datasets are configured with filtering waterfall relationship between 2 or more Keywords Types that are configured to use datasets.

Each Keyword Type configured in the Cascading Dataset configuration will be used to filter the next set values for the next Keyword Type. For example, if there are three Keyword Types that are part of the cascade there would be a 'root' or top level Keyword Type. Once a value is selected, the root value is then used to filter out the next or child Keyword Type Dataset. Finally, when the second or first child value is selected, it is then used to filter the last Keyword Type Dataset.

External Keyword Dataset
External Datasets are an extension of the Standalone Datasets. It provides the ability retrieve values from external source outside of OnBase. Sources such as a third-party database or an accessible web service that connects to third-party system.

If the standard OnBase Dataset functionality does not provide enough flexibility then it is possible use a Unity Script to acquire the data needed. Is functionality is done through the use of IExternalKeywordDataSetScript interface. This is one of the many Unity Script Interfaces

Autofill Keyword Sets
AutoFill Keyword Sets, commonly referred to as "Keysets," refer to a specific set of functionality within OnBase that allow the user to define relationships between a Primary Keyword and one or more Secondary Keywords. Keysets allow for the rapid lookup of Secondary Keywords associated with a provided Primary Keyword.

Keysets vs. Keyset Records
It is important to recognize the distinction between a Keyset and a Keyset Record. A Keyset is a particular association between a Primary Keyword Type and one or more Secondary Keyword Types, as configured in OnBase. Keysets themselves must be created within the OnBase Configuration module.

A Keyset Record is a specific instance of a that particular Keyset.

  Tip

Remember that a Keyset is simply an association between Keyword Types and must be created in OnBase configuration. For Example: "Social Security Number" => "First Name", "Last Name", "Date of Birth"

In this example, "Social Security Number" is the Primary Keyword Type. "First Name", "Last Name", and "Date of Birth" are all Secondary Keyword Types associated with each distinct social security number.

An example of a Keyset Record for this Keyset could then be: "000-00-0000" => "Antonio", "Vivaldi", "03/04/1678"

Using Keyset and Keyset Records
Custom scripts and applications that use the OnBase Unity API are able to programmatically create new Keyset Records as well as access and manipulate those that already exist.

  Note

The user must have rights to Create, Update and Delete a Keyset. There are no user specific rights associated with Retrieve.

Specifically, using the Unity API, a programmer is able to perform the following actions:

Create a new Keyset Record

Retrieve Keyset Records with a particular Primary Keyword value ("keyset expansion")

Update one or all existing Keyset Records with a particular Primary Keyword value

Delete an existing Keyset Record

Tips for Working with Keyset Records
Blank Keywords
If you are updating a Keyset Record and one of the Keyword values needs to be removed or set to an empty value, you should use the CreateBlankKeyword method off the KeywordType object. This method will return an object of type Keyword with its IsBlank property set to true. When retrieving Keyword values, this property should be checked prior to retrieval, in order to avoid an exception being thrown.

Primary Keywords
Primary Keywords cannot be updated. An exception will be thrown if you attempt to do so.

Keywords in Unity
In the Unity programming model, the Keywords that belong to a given document are grouped together into Keyword Records which are used to classify and logically group the Keywords. When a developer needs to access, modify, or query against these Keywords, they will be interacting with one of three Unity Keyword Record classes, each of which has a distinct purpose within the Unity object model.

Image 33
Unity Keyword Records
Keyword Records are containers that allow Keywords to be grouped together, and allow developers to easily identify whether/how Keywords are grouped together. The records are grouped into the following Record Types:

Standalone Keyword Record Type
Standalone Keywords are added to a document, one Keyword Record at a time. Unlike other Keyword Records, Keywords within this record are not grouped with other Keywords. This allows multiple instances of a given Keyword Type within this record. This is the same behavior exhibited by the OnBase Client. A Document object can also never have more than one Standalone Keyword Record. The Standalone Keyword Record will always have a KeywordRecordType of Standalone.

Single-Instance Keyword Record Type
In OnBase Configuration, administrators may group Keyword Types together into Keyword Type Groups to enhance performance. Keyword Types that belong to the Keyword Type Group may only be assigned one value. In other words, a given Keyword Type Group may only contain a single instance of the Keywords within the group. If the Keyword Type Group is then configured such that it does not allow multiple instances of the Keyword Type Group, it is referred to as a Single-Instance Keyword Record in the Unity API.

In the Unity model, each Single-Instance Keyword Record corresponds to a Keyword Type Group, and contains a list of all Keywords assigned to the document that are part of that same Keyword Type Group. These records will have a KeywordRecordType.RecordType of SingleInstance. The KeywordRecordType.Name and KeywordRecordType.ID will correspond to the name and ID of the Keyword Type Group configured in OnBase.

Multi-Instance Keyword Record Type
Multi-Instance Keyword Type Groups are simply Keyword Type Groups that can have multiple instances of the group on a document. OnBase retains the grouping for each set of values on the document. In the Unity programming model, these Keywords are accessed via Multi-Instance Keyword Records.

In the Unity model, each Multi-Instance Keyword Record corresponds to a grouping of Keyword values that belong to a given Multi-Instance Keyword Type Group. If there are multiple instances of Keywords in the Keyword Type Group on a document, each instance will belong to a separate Multi-Instance Keyword Record. These records will have a KeywordRecordType.RecordType of MultiInstance. The KeywordRecordType.Name and KeywordRecordType.ID will correspond to the name and ID of the Keyword Type Group configured in OnBase.

